Email Campaign

Jacob Igel & Samuel Vaughan

Last complied on April 20, 2023

We are interested in designing a campaign that will maximize the response rate. We are very sure, based on experience, that there are four drivers for this process. However, we have no idea how those factors might interact. The factors are shown below.

  1. What type of design would you recommend for this situation?
  • 2^k factorial design
  1. Construct that design below. Use the FrF2 package.
library(FrF2)
d<-FrF2(nruns=16, nfactors=4, randomize = TRUE)
d

## 16  1 -1  1  1
## class=design, type= full factorial
  1. That was just for fun. Now read in the file “EmailCampaign.csv”.

  1. What is the highest order interaction effect we can estimate with this design?
  • 4 way interaction (A, B, C, D)
  1. Fit the Saturated model.
reg<-lm(y~A*B*C*D, data=df)

  1. Analyze this design with a half normal plot. What effects look significant? Remember you can change alpha=0.95 to show the labels of all of the effects.
hncoeff<-halfnormal(reg, alpha=0.95)$coef
pse<-ME.Lenth(hncoeff)$PSE
abline(a=0, b=1/pse)

* From this plot, we can see that D and B are teh effects that look the most significant.

  1. Construct an interaction plot matrix for this experiment. What do you observe?
library(FrF2)
IAPlot(reg)

* We can see that A and C might have an interesting interaction * Possibly B and C have an interaction, need to do further testing.

  1. Check the assumptions. State the assumption you are checking with each plot.

Check for Normality

qqnorm(reg6$residuals)
qqline(reg6$residuals)

Checking for a trend (Specifically no trend)

plot(reg6$residuals)

Checking for a pattern (specifically no pattern)

plot(reg6$residuals, reg6$fitted.values)

  1. Construct the three-way interaction plots for this model. There is no need to look at the two-way interactions since all factors are involved in a three-way interaction.
library(sjPlot)

  1. What are the optimal settings? I based these on the three way interaction plots.
  • D: +1
  • A: -1
  • C: +1
  • B: -1
  1. What is the predicted response for these settings?
optimal<-data.frame(A=-1, B=-1, D=1, C=1)
predict(reg6, optimal, interval="confidence")
